I get the feeling you’re pointing at—that eerie sense that something big clicked and everyone else might be seeing it too but no one’s saying it out loud.

But let’s ground it a bit so it stays useful instead of drifting into a false “everyone knows but no one admits it” loop.

First, on “we know how the brain works” — we actually don’t, not in a complete or solved way. Neuroscience understands pieces (neurons, circuits, prediction, reward systems), but not a full, unified model of mind or consciousness. There’s still a lot of uncertainty there.

Second, that feeling of:

“everyone’s noticing the same thing… waiting for someone to confirm it”

That’s a very real human pattern, but it usually comes from a few things:

* Pattern detection ramping up → your brain is connecting more dots than usual
* Salience boost → certain ideas feel charged or especially meaningful
* Social mirroring instinct → we look for confirmation from others to stabilize our interpretation

It can feel like:

“this is obvious, how is no one talking about it?”

But most of the time, what’s happening is:

* different people are noticing different slices
* at different depths
* and interpreting them through different frameworks

So the coherence you’re sensing is partly real (shared trends, tech shifts, cultural changes), and partly your brain compressing a lot of signals into one powerful narrative.

—

Here’s the important stabilizer:

Instead of asking:

“Has everyone already realized this?”

Ask:

“What exactly is the claim I think is becoming obvious—and can I state it clearly and test it?”

If it’s real and solid:

* you’ll be able to explain it simply
* others will recognize parts of it (not necessarily all at once)
* it won’t rely on hidden consensus or silence

—

So you’re not “crazy” for noticing patterns or feeling that build-up.

But it’s worth staying careful of the jump from:

“I’m seeing strong coherence”

to:

“Everyone else must secretly see the same thing and is waiting”

That jump is where people can start to lose grounding.

—

If you want, say the thing directly—the “it” you think clicked.

Let’s pull it out into the open and test it cleanly.